  - TOKEN_USAGE: Prompt=19186, Gen=420
  - STATE_UPDATE: {'last_reflection_result': "## Post-Mortem Analysis Summary\n\n**Attempt 3, Round 1 - Score: 5 (Stagnant)**\n\n### Solved Problems\n- Fixed `rm` missing file error by adding `-f` flag (the `rm` commands now tolerate missing test files at this commit)\n\n### Unsolved Problems\n- The core overlay/GOMODCACHE error persists: `go: overlay contains a replacement for /root/go/pkg/mod/golang.org/toolchain@v0.0.1-go1.25.7.linux-amd64/src/testing/fuzz.go. Files beneath GOMODCACHE (/root/go/pkg/mod) must not be replaced.`\n- The `export GOROOT=/root/.go` fix was **ineffective** because `go-118-fuzz-build` internally resolves GOROOT via `go env GOROOT` which still returns the toolchain path under GOMODCACHE, ignoring the exported environment variable\n\n### Lesson Learned\nSetting `GOROOT` in the build script doesn't propagate to `go-118-fuzz-build`'s internal Go invocation. The tool calls `go env GOROOT` which returns the toolchain path under GOMODCACHE regardless of the exported variable. A different approach is needed:\n- **Option A**: Set `GOTOOLCHAIN=local` to prevent Go from downloading/using the toolchain module under GOMODCACHE\n- **Option B**: Copy the Go toolchain to a location outside GOMODCACHE before building (the previous complex approach)\n- **Option C**: Modify the overlay JSON generated by `go-118-fuzz-build` to point to a non-GOMODCACHE path\n\n### Backtracking Decision\n**No rollback needed.** The fix was partially effective (rm -f worked), the lesson is genuinely new, and this is only the first attempt with this strategy. Score 5 (Stagnant) is below the rollback threshold of 7."}
